{"cursor":"17257","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n portrait of Linus Pauling wearing a mortarboard, 1922]] The 'square academic\n cap', 'graduate cap', or\n 'mortarboard' [http://www.bartleby.com/61/1/M0430100.html mortarboard. The\n American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language: Fourth Edition. 2000 ] (because of its similarity in appearance to the\n hawk used by bricklayers to hold\n mortar [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/mortarboard Mortarboard].\n dictionary.com ) or Oxford cap, is an item of academic head dress\n consisting of a horizontal square board fixed upon a skull-cap, with a tassel\n attached to the center. In the UK and the US, it is commonly referred to\n informally in conjunction with an academic gown worn as a cap and gown. It is\n also often termed a 'square', 'trencher', or 'corner-cap' in Australia. The\n adjective 'academical' is also used. [http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/univ/so/p-\n dfs/cso_4_ordinance02.171_217.pdf] University of Cambridge Ordinances, Chapter\n II In the US and UK, it is usually referred to more generically as a\n mortarboard, or (in the U.S.) simply 'cap'.\n\nThe cap, together with the gown and (sometimes) a hood, now form the customary\nuniform of a university graduate, in many parts of the world, following a\nBritish model.\n: Ludovico Gonzaga, 1474.]]\n","linknr":274,"url":"Square_academic_cap","recorded":1362566586,"links":33,"instances":["color","cap","color","color","color","color","color","color","color","mouse","color","color","color","color","color","color","color","academic_discipline"],"pdf":["http://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/univ/so/pdfs/cso_4_ordinance02.171_217.pdf"],"categories":["Academic dress","Caps","Graduation","Hats","Headgear"],"headings":["Origins","Variants","Tassel","Traditional wear","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ca/LinusPaulingGraduation1922.jpg/220px-LinusPaulingGraduation1922.jpg","//bits.wiki